<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="chapter-q1">
  <title>Question 1: Understanding Simpson's Paradox</title>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this chapter, you will encounter your first major analytical challenge: 
      understanding how aggregate data can mask important patterns when context matters.
      This phenomenon, known as Simpson's Paradox, is crucial for making sound 
      recommendations in real-world situations.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <!-- Q1 Large Dataset -->
  <section xml:id="Q1-large">
    <title>Question 1 - Large Dataset</title>
    
    <p>
      You arrive just before planting. The air is dry and hot, and farmers are already gathering in the shade. One of the farmers spots you, and comes running over.
    </p>

    <p>
      <q>Aminou! Thank goodness you're here. We've heard about your big study across the three countries. Everyone says you now have real evidence. So tell me - what variety should I plant?</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      You pause. Across Ilam, Regin, and Anikrub, thousands of plots were studied. Farmers tried two varieties: ICRI and Locale.
    </p>

    <p>
      You have the data and so you sit down with them to give them some advice. What do you say?
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Choose your answer:</alert>
      <ul>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-icri">ICRI</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-locale">Locale</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-either">Either</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-idk">I don't know</xref></p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="Q1-large-icri">
    <title>ICRI - Large Dataset</title>
    
    <p>
      You nod confidently, <q>Plant ICRI.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer squints at you, <q>Hmm.</q> They're not convinced, and that plays on your mind.
    </p>

    <p>
      Later that evening, as you sit reviewing the data more carefully, something unsettles you.
    </p>

    <p>
      <q>Wait<ellipsis/> what?</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      You realize that you may have made a mistake. When you look at the overall average across all three countries, ICRI looks better. That much is true.
    </p>

    <p>
      But when you break the data down by individual country, you notice something odd.
      Within Anikrub, Locale actually outperforms ICRI.
      Within Regin, Locale also has a slight edge.
      And in Ilam<ellipsis/> well, ICRI does seem a bit better there, but only slightly.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>How could ICRI win overall, yet lose (or tie) in every individual country?</alert>
    </p>

    <p>
      You realise it's because the data are unbalanced. More ICRI trials happened in Ilam, where ICRI does well, and more Locale trials happened in Anikrub, where Locale does well. The overall average is biased by where the trials happened.
    </p>

    <p>
      You now realise that the aggregate result was misleading, and that context-specific advice would be better.
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer you spoke to lives in Anikrub.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>What should you have told them?</alert>
      <ul>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-icri-icri">ICRI</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-icri-locale">Locale</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-icri-either">Either</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-icri-idk">I don't know</xref></p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="Q1-large-icri-icri">
    <title>ICRI Again - Large Dataset</title>
    
    <p>
      You shake your head. No. That doesn't help.
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer is in Anikrub. When you check the data again, within Anikrub, Locale outperforms ICRI.
    </p>

    <p>
      You made the same mistake twice: recommending based on an overall average without accounting for the farmer's specific context.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is <alert>Simpson's Paradox</alert> at work - where an aggregate result reverses when data is broken down by subgroups.
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer asked you what variety they should plant. You gave advice. But you gave advice based on aggregate data that did not reflect their reality.
    </p>

    <p>
      Real data, real farmers, real consequences.
    </p>

    <p>
      Let's try again. The farmer is in Anikrub. What should you recommend?
      <ul>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-help">ICRI</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-locale-correct">Locale</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-help">Either</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-help">I don't know</xref></p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="Q1-large-icri-either">
    <title>Either - Large Dataset (After ICRI)</title>
    
    <p>
      No, that's still not right.
    </p>

    <p>
