    </p>

    <p>
      When you break down the results by region, you see that in Anikrub specifically, Locale outperforms ICRI.
    </p>

    <p>
      Your job as a statistician is not just to collect data - it's to interpret it carefully and give context-appropriate recommendations.
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer in Anikrub deserves better than uncertainty when you actually have clear evidence for their context.
    </p>

    <p>
      Let's try again. The farmer is in Anikrub. What should you recommend?
      <ul>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-help">ICRI</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-locale-correct">Locale</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-help">Either</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-large-help">I don't know</xref></p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="Q1-large-icri-locale">
    <title>Correcting Course - Large Dataset</title>
    
    <p>
      Yes.
    </p>

    <p>
      For a farmer in Anikrub, you should recommend Locale.
    </p>

    <p>
      You've just experienced <alert>Simpson's Paradox</alert> - a phenomenon where an aggregate pattern reverses when data is broken down into subgroups.
    </p>

    <p>
      In this case:
      <ul>
        <li><p>Across all countries, ICRI looked better on average.</p></li>
        <li><p>But within each individual country, Locale performed as well or better.</p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
      The paradox occurred because more ICRI trials happened in regions where ICRI did relatively well, and more Locale trials happened where Locale did relatively well. The aggregate average was biased by where trials were conducted.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>The lesson:</alert> Always disaggregate when context matters. Overall averages can be dangerously misleading.
    </p>

    <p>
      Continue to <xref ref="Q2-large">Question 2</xref>.
    </p>
  </section>

